## 5. Compatibility & Setup Guide

- Best Blade Matches
    - Outer Carbon: Great match. The crisp, hard nature of outer carbon (like Viscaria or Timo Boll ALC) perfectly compensates for the softer sponge and provides the missing top-end speed.
    - Inner Carbon: Very safe, spin-oriented setup. Creates a massive dwell time, ideal for loop-dominant players (e.g., Hurricane Long 5).
    - All-Wood: Good for development, but might feel too slow for competitive play at mid-distance.
    - Mismatch Cases: Avoid ultra-soft, highly flexible all-wood blades (like Stiga Allround Classic). The combination will feel too mushy and lack put-away power.

- Forehand vs. Backhand Recommendation
    - Forehand: Recommended only for developing players, or those who prefer a highly controlled, spin-first forehand over outright power.
    - Backhand: Highly recommended. This rubber was practically built for the modern backhand—perfect for chiquitas, opening loops, and active blocking.

